{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "DahnekeHeatTransportCorrection",
        "description": "Transition-regime correction factor β_q for heat conduction to a sphere, Dahneke (1983) Eq. 5.7. Computes the heat-transfer Knudsen number Kn_K = 2κ/(c̄_gas n_gas m_gas c_v r) and the correction factor β_q = (Kn_K+1)/(2 Kn_K(Kn_K+1)/α_t + 1). The corrected heat conduction rate is Q = β_q · Q_M where Q_M = 4π r κ (T_inf − T_o) is the Maxwell (continuum) rate. Migrated from Aerosol.jl src/dahneke_brownian_diffusion.jl `DahnekeHeatTransportCorrection`.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "heat-transfer",
            "transition-regime",
            "dahneke",
            "knudsen-number",
            "accommodation-coefficient"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-21T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "Aerosol.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-03p)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Dahneke, B. (1983). Simple Kinetic Theory of Brownian Diffusion in Vapors and Aerosols. In Theory of Dispersed Multiphase Flow (pp. 97–133). Academic Press. Eq. 5.7 (heat transport correction factor for transition-regime conduction to a sphere)."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "DahnekeHeatTransportCorrection": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Dahneke, B. (1983) Simple Kinetic Theory of Brownian Diffusion in Vapors and Aerosols. Theory of Dispersed Multiphase Flow, Academic Press, Eq. 5.7 — heat transport correction factor for transition-regime conduction to a sphere. Migrated from Aerosol.jl src/dahneke_brownian_diffusion.jl `DahnekeHeatTransportCorrection` (esm-03p).",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@481d5b6:src/dahneke_brownian_diffusion.jl:93\n\nUpstream `DahnekeHeatTransportCorrection` is an MTK `@component` with 5 parameters (n_gas, c_bar_gas, c_v, m_gas, α_t), 2 shared parameters (r, κ connected via param_to_var), and 2 algebraic variables (Kn_K, β_q) with no time derivatives — both purely observed.\n\nEquations (Dahneke 1983, Eq. 5.7):\n  Kn_K = 2κ / (c_bar_gas · n_gas · m_gas · c_v · r)   [heat-transfer Knudsen number]\n  β_q  = (Kn_K + 1) / (2 Kn_K (Kn_K + 1) / α_t + 1) [heat transport correction factor]\n\nPhysical interpretation:\n  The denominator c_bar_gas · n_gas · m_gas · c_v · r is proportional to the continuum\n  heat flux per unit temperature difference. At Kn_K = 0 (continuum), β_q = 1 and the\n  corrected rate equals the Maxwell rate. At Kn_K → ∞ (free-molecular), β_q → α_t/(2 Kn_K),\n  so the correction grows small and the heat flux is suppressed by the thermal accommodation\n  coefficient α_t.\n\nDefault conditions (r=100 nm, air at 298 K):\n  Kn_K ≈ 1.224 (transition regime)\n  β_q  ≈ 0.345\n\nThis component is used as a subsystem (heat_corr) inside DahnekeCondensationEvaporation,\nwhere the corrected conduction rate Q = β_q · Q_M couples mass and heat transport. The\nstandalone component exposes only Kn_K and β_q; Q_M and Q are computed at the coupling level.\n\nTopological evaluation order: r, κ → Kn_K → β_q. Acyclic, depth 2.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-12): purely algebraic chain of depth 2 in float64.\nRound-off is ~2×10⁻¹⁵ per arithmetic node; rel=1e-12 leaves three orders of headroom above\nmachine epsilon."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "κ": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "W/(m*K)",
                    "default": 0.026,
                    "description": "Thermal conductivity of the carrier gas. Enters Kn_K as the numerator 2κ and Q_M as 4π r κ ΔT. Default 0.026 W/(m·K) is air at 298 K and 1 atm. Should be updated for non-air carrier gases."
                },
                "n_gas": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.46e+25,
                    "description": "Number concentration of gas molecules. Used in the heat Knudsen number Kn_K via the volumetric heat capacity n_gas × m_gas × c_v. Default 2.46×10²⁵ m⁻³ is air at STP (Loschmidt constant)."
                },
                "c_bar_gas": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 500.0,
                    "description": "Mean thermal velocity of gas (carrier) molecules. Used in the heat Knudsen number Kn_K = 2κ/(c_bar_gas n_gas m_gas c_v r). Default 500 m/s is approximate for N₂ at 298 K (exact value ~476 m/s; 500 m/s is the round-number value used in the source)."
                },
                "c_v": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/(kg*K)",
                    "default": 718.0,
                    "description": "Specific heat at constant volume of the carrier gas (per unit mass). Used in Kn_K via the volumetric heat capacity n_gas × m_gas × c_v. Default 718.0 J/(kg·K) is for air (diatomic ideal gas: c_v = (5/2)(R/M_air) ≈ 718 J/(kg·K))."
                },
                "m_gas": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 4.81e-26,
                    "description": "Mass of a single gas (carrier) molecule. Used in Kn_K to form the volumetric heat capacity n_gas × m_gas × c_v. Default 4.81e-26 kg ≈ N₂ (0.028 kg/mol / Avogadro). Should match the actual carrier gas species."
                },
                "α_t": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 1.0,
                    "description": "Thermal accommodation coefficient: fraction of impinging gas molecules that fully thermally accommodate to the droplet surface. Dimensionless, range (0, 1]. Default 1.0 (perfect thermal accommodation). Controls the free-molecular limit: β_q → α_t/(2 Kn_K) as Kn_K → ∞. Partial accommodation (α_t < 1) reduces the correction factor below the α_t=1 curve at all Kn_K."
                },
                "r": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1e-07,
                    "description": "Droplet (particle) radius. Appears in the denominator of Kn_K so that Kn_K ∝ 1/r — smaller particles are deeper in the transition or free-molecular regime. Default 100 nm places the system in the transition regime (Kn_K ≈ 1.224 at default conditions)."
                },
                "Kn_K": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Heat-transfer Knudsen number, Eq. 5.7: Kn_K = 2κ / (c_bar_gas n_gas m_gas c_v r). The denominator is proportional to the continuum volumetric heat flux coefficient. Kn_K ≪ 1 → continuum heat transfer (β_q → 1); Kn_K ≫ 1 → free-molecular heat transfer (β_q → α_t / (2 Kn_K)). At default conditions Kn_K ≈ 1.224.",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": [2.0, "κ"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["c_bar_gas", "n_gas", "m_gas", "c_v", "r"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                "β_q": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Heat transport correction factor, Eq. 5.7: β_q = (Kn_K+1) / (2 Kn_K(Kn_K+1)/α_t + 1). Scales the Maxwell heat conduction rate to the transition-regime rate Q = β_q · Q_M. Limits: β_q → 1 as Kn_K → 0 (continuum); β_q → α_t/(2 Kn_K) → 0 as Kn_K → ∞ (free-molecular). At default conditions β_q ≈ 0.345.",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "+", "args": ["Kn_K", 1.0]},
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            {"op": "*", "args": [2.0, "Kn_K", {"op": "+", "args": ["Kn_K", 1.0]}]},
                                            "α_t"
                                        ]
                                    },
                                    1.0
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            },
            "equations": [],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "default_parameters",
                    "description": "Default parameters: κ=0.026 W/(m·K), n_gas=2.46e25 m⁻³, c_bar_gas=500 m/s, c_v=718 J/(kg·K), m_gas=4.81e-26 kg, α_t=1.0, r=100 nm. Kn_K = 2×0.026 / (500×2.46e25×4.81e-26×718×1e-7) ≈ 1.224 (transition regime). β_q ≈ 0.345.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "Kn_K", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.2241332983231208, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}},
                        {"variable": "β_q",  "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.3450798590680775, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "continuum_limit_large_r",
                    "description": "Continuum limit: r=0.01 m → Kn_K ≈ 1.224e-5 ≪ 1. β_q approaches 1 from below: β_q ≈ 1 − Kn_K → 0.999988. Verifies that large particles recover the Maxwell continuum heat conduction rate.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"r": 0.01},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "Kn_K", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.2241332983231207e-05, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}},
                        {"variable": "β_q",  "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.9999877586670204,    "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "free_molecular_small_r",
                    "description": "Free-molecular limit: r=1 nm → Kn_K ≈ 122.4 ≫ 1. β_q ≈ α_t/(2 Kn_K) ≈ 1/(2×122.4) ≈ 0.00408. Verifies that very small particles suppress heat transfer toward the kinetic limit.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"r": 1e-09},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "Kn_K", "time": 0.0, "expected": 122.41332983231206,   "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}},
                        {"variable": "β_q",  "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.004084387321960984, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "partial_thermal_accommodation",
                    "description": "Partial accommodation: α_t=0.5. Kn_K unchanged (α_t does not enter Kn_K). β_q is reduced compared to the perfect-accommodation case: β_q(α_t=0.5) ≈ 0.187 vs β_q(α_t=1.0) ≈ 0.345. The free-molecular limit halves: β_q → α_t/(2 Kn_K) = 0.5/(2 Kn_K).",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"α_t": 0.5},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "Kn_K", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.2241332983231208, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}},
                        {"variable": "β_q",  "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.187050615587378,  "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "kn_k_inversely_proportional_to_r",
                    "description": "Kn_K ∝ 1/r: doubling r from 100 nm to 200 nm halves Kn_K from ≈1.224 to ≈0.612. β_q increases toward 1 as the system moves toward continuum.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"r": 2e-07},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "Kn_K", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.6120666491615604, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}},
                        {"variable": "β_q",  "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.5421655586376863, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "kn_k_proportional_to_kappa",
                    "description": "Kn_K ∝ κ: doubling κ from 0.026 to 0.052 doubles Kn_K from ≈1.224 to ≈2.448. β_q decreases as the system moves deeper into the transition regime.",
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_overrides": {"κ": 0.052},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "Kn_K", "time": 0.0, "expected": 2.4482665966462416, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}},
                        {"variable": "β_q",  "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.1928069892724093, "tolerance": {"rel": 1e-12}}
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "beta_q_vs_r",
                    "description": "Heat transport correction factor β_q as a function of droplet radius r (log sweep 1 nm to 10 µm) with α_t=1.0 and default gas properties. β_q decreases monotonically from near 1 (continuum, large r) toward 0 (free-molecular, small r), showing that transition-regime corrections are most important in the 10–500 nm size range.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "r",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 1e-09,
                                    "stop": 1e-05,
                                    "count": 81,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "beta_q_vs_r",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "β_q vs droplet radius r. β_q → 1 for large r (continuum), β_q → 0 for small r (free-molecular). Transition occurs around Kn_K ~ 1, i.e. r ~ 2κ/(c̄_gas n_gas m_gas c_v) ≈ 82 nm at default gas conditions.",
                            "x": {"variable": "r",   "label": "Droplet radius r (m)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "β_q", "label": "Heat transport correction factor β_q"}
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "kn_k_vs_r",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Kn_K vs droplet radius r. Kn_K ∝ 1/r — small particles are deep in the free-molecular regime.",
                            "x": {"variable": "r",    "label": "Droplet radius r (m)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "Kn_K", "label": "Heat Knudsen number Kn_K"}
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "beta_q_vs_alpha_t",
                    "description": "Sensitivity of β_q to the thermal accommodation coefficient α_t (linear sweep 0.1 to 1.0) at default radius r=100 nm. β_q scales roughly linearly with α_t in the transition regime; the curve flattens toward α_t=1. This illustrates the role of surface accommodation in controlling gas-phase heat transfer to nano-scale particles.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "α_t",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 0.1,
                                    "stop": 1.0,
                                    "count": 19,
                                    "scale": "linear"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "beta_q_vs_alpha_t",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "β_q vs thermal accommodation coefficient α_t at r=100 nm (transition regime, Kn_K≈1.224). β_q increases with α_t, reaching 0.345 at α_t=1.0.",
                            "x": {"variable": "α_t", "label": "Thermal accommodation coefficient α_t"},
                            "y": {"variable": "β_q", "label": "Heat transport correction factor β_q"}
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
